00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:46.420
The underlying theme of my two lectures

00:04:46.420 --> 00:04:49.470
is really that most of
the major questions,

00:04:49.470 --> 00:04:50.940
important questions in biology,

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:52.840
are solved by an integrative approach

00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:55.670
that unites fields from
diverse disciplines.

00:04:55.670 --> 00:04:57.810
That what defines us are our questions.

00:04:57.810 --> 00:05:01.070
And that the tools we use
can span multiple fields.

00:05:01.070 --> 00:05:04.150
And this is nowhere more
true in evolutionary biology.

00:05:04.150 --> 00:05:06.530
In particular in those parts
of evolutionary biology

00:05:06.530 --> 00:05:08.580
where we're trying to
reconstruct and understand

00:05:08.580 --> 00:05:09.650
evolutionary history

00:05:11.410 --> 00:05:14.000
Now, in stepping back a bit,

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.750
really, when we think about
this being the Darwin year,

00:05:17.800 --> 00:05:21.630
two great concepts really stem
from The Origin of Species

00:05:21.630 --> 00:05:23.050
by Charles Darwin.

00:05:23.050 --> 00:05:24.680
I mean, the first is
obviously natural selection,

00:05:24.680 --> 00:05:26.840
that there's a struggle for existence

00:05:26.840 --> 00:05:29.970
that brings about a change
in populations over time.

00:05:29.970 --> 00:05:31.270
The other, and the one that really

00:05:31.270 --> 00:05:32.930
has captured my imagination,

00:05:32.930 --> 00:05:36.090
is the notion of descent
with modification.

00:05:36.090 --> 00:05:38.180
That it is just like we
are modified descendants

00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:39.120
of our parents,

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:41.740
and understanding that
descent with modification

00:05:41.740 --> 00:05:45.000
in our own family enables
us to see our family trees,

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.090
that our family tree
extends to other species,

00:05:48.090 --> 00:05:50.420
and our own species is
a modified descendant

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:53.110
of other species that had
existed in the distant past.

00:05:53.110 --> 00:05:55.870
And that through this process
of descent with modification,

00:05:55.870 --> 00:05:57.970
the very simple beginnings can produce

00:05:57.970 --> 00:06:00.660
an extraordinary evolutionary tree.

00:06:00.660 --> 00:06:02.890
And it's really that's what
I'm gonna focus on today.

00:06:02.890 --> 00:06:05.260
Yesterday, the take-home message was,

00:06:05.260 --> 00:06:07.250
those of you who were
awake for the last slide,

00:06:07.250 --> 00:06:09.933
saw that evolutionary
trees are very important,

00:06:09.933 --> 00:06:12.610
that we can make very strong predictions

00:06:12.610 --> 00:06:14.450
about where to find fossils

00:06:14.450 --> 00:06:17.600
that answer major gaps in
our knowledge of evolution.

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:19.460
And at the way we can best interpret them

00:06:19.460 --> 00:06:23.080
is not as a linear series of
events, a ladder-like process,

00:06:23.080 --> 00:06:25.350
but really is understanding
them as a branching tree

00:06:25.350 --> 00:06:29.900
of diversity and adaptive
diversification and radiation.

00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:31.620
And so, to understand that,

00:06:31.620 --> 00:06:33.130
we really kind of looked at the level

00:06:33.130 --> 00:06:34.900
of whole animals yesterday.

00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:37.310
Today, we're gonna take
a sort of bore in a bit,

00:06:37.310 --> 00:06:39.960
and look at organs, how
do new organs arise,

00:06:39.960 --> 00:06:41.830
through change, through time.

00:06:41.830 --> 00:06:43.230
When you look at organs

00:06:43.230 --> 00:06:45.660
with a principle of
descent with modification,

00:06:45.660 --> 00:06:46.880
really becomes very clear

00:06:46.880 --> 00:06:49.680
that to understand "the new" in evolution,

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:51.610
you have to understand the old.

00:06:51.610 --> 00:06:54.080
Because often what we
have to do is trace organs

00:06:54.080 --> 00:06:57.260
through time to understand
what the same organ is

00:06:57.260 --> 00:06:59.410
in different species over time,

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:00.900
To understand the sequence of changes

00:07:00.900 --> 00:07:04.070
that happen in an organ from
one species to the next,

00:07:04.070 --> 00:07:06.650
we have to find a way of
defining what the same is.

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:07.483
What's sameness?

00:07:07.483 --> 00:07:10.090
What's the same organ in
two different creatures?

00:07:10.090 --> 00:07:13.480
So, to understand novelty
or new organs over time,

00:07:13.480 --> 00:07:15.350
we really have to understand the old,

00:07:15.350 --> 00:07:18.040
and that means understanding
what is the same structure

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:19.810
in different kinds of creatures.

00:07:19.810 --> 00:07:21.730
Now, at first glance,
you could not imagine

00:07:21.730 --> 00:07:23.510
a subject more boring or esoteric

00:07:23.510 --> 00:07:24.570
than trying to come to grips

00:07:24.570 --> 00:07:27.280
with what's the same in evolution.

00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:28.660
But I'm gonna tell you that it's actually,

00:07:28.660 --> 00:07:31.300
arguably, one of the
most important concepts

00:07:31.300 --> 00:07:32.500
in all of biology.

00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:34.080
And so much of what we do

00:07:34.080 --> 00:07:36.600
as comparative biologists,
evolutionary biologists,

00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:39.460
and even people interested
in biomedical discovery,

00:07:39.460 --> 00:07:40.780
stems from that.

00:07:40.780 --> 00:07:42.100
And where to begin?

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:44.120
We begin with noses.

00:07:44.120 --> 00:07:46.860
So, here is a famous nose.

00:07:46.860 --> 00:07:50.470
This is Basil Rathbone
from Sherlock Holmes.

00:07:50.470 --> 00:07:51.600
And the question really is,

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:53.650
what is a nose in different species?

00:07:53.650 --> 00:07:57.470
Is it the same as a nose in
some other kind of creature,

00:07:57.470 --> 00:07:58.580
like this creature here,

00:07:58.580 --> 00:08:02.460
with this object perched at
the end of it? (chuckles)

00:08:02.460 --> 00:08:04.950
Is it the same as this proboscis

00:08:04.950 --> 00:08:06.120
at the end of this creature?

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:09.150
Is it the same organ in
these different species?

00:08:09.150 --> 00:08:11.860
Is it the same as a bill of a bird,

00:08:11.860 --> 00:08:15.420
of the giant proboscis of a paddlefish,

00:08:15.420 --> 00:08:17.150
or the many different kinds of probosci

00:08:17.150 --> 00:08:19.750
we find in arthropods and other creatures?

00:08:19.750 --> 00:08:21.250
Are these the same structures?

00:08:21.250 --> 00:08:22.360
How do we know it?

00:08:22.360 --> 00:08:24.600
What does it mean in
biology to be the same?

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:27.190
This is the starting
point for understanding

00:08:27.190 --> 00:08:29.887
how new features arise over time.

00:08:29.887 --> 00:08:31.790
Now, you can say, "Wow, that's
really kind of esoteric.

00:08:31.790 --> 00:08:33.010
Thanks for getting into that."

00:08:33.010 --> 00:08:34.070
But I will tell you

00:08:34.070 --> 00:08:36.690
that it's arguably one of
the most important concepts

00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:38.090
in biology, as I've said before.

00:08:38.090 --> 00:08:41.090
And so much of what, that
exists of why it's important,

00:08:41.090 --> 00:08:43.960
we take for granted, as
biomedical researchers.

00:08:43.960 --> 00:08:46.270
Look at the title of this paper.

00:08:46.270 --> 00:08:49.700
Animal models of human disease:
zebrafish swim into view.

00:08:49.700 --> 00:08:51.440
Zebrafish and their
development are a model

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:55.210
for human blood formation,
formation of the pancreas,

00:08:55.210 --> 00:08:57.020
and diabetes models, and so forth.

00:08:57.020 --> 00:08:59.240
It's a model for biomedical discovery.

00:08:59.240 --> 00:09:00.780
Why stop at fish?

00:09:00.780 --> 00:09:03.330
A Drosophila model for
Parkinson's disease.

00:09:03.330 --> 00:09:04.860
The only way to understanding that

00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:07.410
is really understanding that
what the events we're seeing

00:09:07.410 --> 00:09:09.480
in Drosophila are the same,

00:09:09.480 --> 00:09:13.650
in this flying insect, in humans.

00:09:13.650 --> 00:09:16.740
Indeed, if you ever need an example of why

00:09:16.740 --> 00:09:20.080
evolutionary connections to
the rest of life on this planet

00:09:20.080 --> 00:09:23.190
are important, I encourage
you to a website.

00:09:23.190 --> 00:09:25.920
And that website is the
Nobel Prize in Medicine.

00:09:25.920 --> 00:09:27.370
And what you see here is a list

00:09:27.370 --> 00:09:31.570
of the Nobel Prizes in Medicine
over the last few years.

00:09:31.570 --> 00:09:33.320
Who've they gone to?

00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:36.280
They've gone to people looking
at Drosophila, fruit fly,

00:09:36.280 --> 00:09:37.960
to understand the genes that,

00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:40.390
many of the genes that
control development.

00:09:40.390 --> 00:09:42.460
Two Nobel Prizes in the last several years

00:09:42.460 --> 00:09:44.470
have gone to people working
on a little tiny worm

00:09:44.470 --> 00:09:47.130
the size of a comma on a piece of paper.

00:09:47.130 --> 00:09:49.650
Yet, that little worm,
Caenorhabditis elegans,

00:09:49.650 --> 00:09:53.900
is telling us how cells die,
kinds of programed cell death,

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:55.960
or how our genes are silenced.

00:09:55.960 --> 00:09:57.950
And indeed, it's discoveries such as that

00:09:57.950 --> 00:09:59.810
which have important ramifications

00:09:59.810 --> 00:10:01.683
to drug design and human health.

00:10:02.810 --> 00:10:04.460
Understanding the cell cycle has

00:10:05.460 --> 00:10:07.190
depended on studies of creatures

00:10:07.190 --> 00:10:09.780
as bizarre as sea urchins and yeast.

00:10:09.780 --> 00:10:10.613
And why stop there?

00:10:10.613 --> 00:10:14.590
Memory and sea slugs, although
not this particular one.

00:10:14.590 --> 00:10:16.950
And of course, since
we have this individual

00:10:16.950 --> 00:10:20.500
on the here, we also learn
about ourselves through corn.

00:10:20.500 --> 00:10:23.170
So, the important thing here is

00:10:23.170 --> 00:10:26.690
by applying, understanding
basic biological discovery

00:10:26.690 --> 00:10:28.050
and applying it to humans,

00:10:28.050 --> 00:10:29.410
we really have to have an understanding

00:10:29.410 --> 00:10:32.640
of what the same is in
different creatures.

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:34.300
Now, like all important concepts,

00:10:34.300 --> 00:10:37.760
this concept has deep,
deep historical roots.

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:40.920
Natural philosophers, indeed,
philosophers for centuries

00:10:40.920 --> 00:10:43.580
have been thinking very
hard about this question.

00:10:43.580 --> 00:10:46.280
And one of the more prominent
players in this regard

00:10:46.280 --> 00:10:48.730
is Sir Richard Owen, shown here.

00:10:48.730 --> 00:10:50.350
This is Richard Owen. He's on your left.

00:10:50.350 --> 00:10:53.070
And Owen was a (audience laughs)

00:10:53.070 --> 00:10:56.830
Owen was an anatomist in the mid-1800's.

00:10:56.830 --> 00:10:58.830
And it was a wonderful
time to be an anatomist

00:10:58.830 --> 00:11:01.780
because you could truly be
a comparative anatomist.

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:03.260
He was fortunate to be an anatomist

00:11:03.260 --> 00:11:05.100
at a time new creatures
were being discovered,

00:11:05.100 --> 00:11:06.280
whole new kinds.

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:08.070
He named Dinosauria.

00:11:08.070 --> 00:11:10.750
He originally described
the skeleton of a gorilla,

00:11:10.750 --> 00:11:11.583
and so forth.

00:11:11.583 --> 00:11:14.260
He was uncovering great natural diversity.

00:11:14.260 --> 00:11:16.510
And in uncovering that
great natural diversity

00:11:16.510 --> 00:11:18.330
of different kinds of
creatures and their skeletons

00:11:18.330 --> 00:11:19.163
and so forth,

00:11:19.163 --> 00:11:22.460
he saw common plans, common designs.

00:11:22.460 --> 00:11:24.800
And this, when I was a graduate student,

00:11:24.800 --> 00:11:26.970
this book, On the Nature of Limbs,

00:11:26.970 --> 00:11:29.250
a discourse by Sir Richard Owen,

00:11:29.250 --> 00:11:31.810
really caught my imagination
in a very big way.

00:11:31.810 --> 00:11:33.520
Because it's in this
book where he lays out,

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:36.300
in a series of figures,
his notion of sameness.

00:11:36.300 --> 00:11:37.610
And he had a couple
different notions here,

00:11:37.610 --> 00:11:39.140
and it's worth spending
a little time on them

00:11:39.140 --> 00:11:40.750
'cause we're gonna touch back to them

00:11:40.750 --> 00:11:42.730
as we get into some experimental work

00:11:42.730 --> 00:11:45.480
that's been happening in my lab lately.

00:11:45.480 --> 00:11:46.790
This figure. It's a beautiful figure.

00:11:46.790 --> 00:11:47.623
It's actually you fold it out.

00:11:47.623 --> 00:11:49.900
It's like ye big in the bind.

00:11:49.900 --> 00:11:51.150
And he shows a human skeleton here.

00:11:51.150 --> 00:11:52.970
And he defines several
different kinds of sameness,

00:11:52.970 --> 00:11:55.660
and right off the bat, he's
laid off the human skeleton

00:11:55.660 --> 00:11:57.420
with birds and other creatures,

00:11:57.420 --> 00:11:59.030
and you could see he's colored it in

00:11:59.030 --> 00:12:02.504
to make specific comparisons
of the same feature

00:12:02.504 --> 00:12:04.070
in different creatures.

00:12:04.070 --> 00:12:07.460
You know, the vertebrae, the
appendages, and so forth.

00:12:07.460 --> 00:12:10.230
And this whole treatise
was really about limbs.

00:12:10.230 --> 00:12:13.120
And he sort of argued, like
many natural philosophers

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:15.970
at the time, for two
different kinds of sameness.

00:12:15.970 --> 00:12:18.700
One is similar features
in different creatures.

00:12:18.700 --> 00:12:21.010
And the other is similar
features in the same creature,

00:12:21.010 --> 00:12:24.263
like arms and legs; they
have a similar sort of plan.

00:12:25.460 --> 00:12:27.240
And you know, the basic
take-home message is

00:12:27.240 --> 00:12:30.710
if you look at the arm of a
human, the wing of a bird,

00:12:30.710 --> 00:12:33.180
or the limb of any limbed animal,

00:12:33.180 --> 00:12:34.880
and you look at the skeleton inside of it,

00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:38.200
there is a common structural
sort of theme or design,

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:40.860
which we have one bone going to two bones

00:12:40.860 --> 00:12:43.620
going to series of small
bones of wrist or ankle bones

00:12:43.620 --> 00:12:44.660
and then the digits.

00:12:44.660 --> 00:12:46.610
You see that both in the leg and the arm,

00:12:46.610 --> 00:12:48.680
and you see it in different species.

00:12:48.680 --> 00:12:50.740
This frog arm here,
actually has two bones,

00:12:50.740 --> 00:12:52.190
but they've been fused up.

00:12:52.190 --> 00:12:55.460
So, the changes we see are
due to changes in the size

00:12:55.460 --> 00:12:58.810
and shape and sometimes
loss of individual bones.

00:12:58.810 --> 00:13:01.010
Now that sameness that
Richard Owen talked about here

00:13:01.010 --> 00:13:03.830
is, between these
appendages, is very different

00:13:03.830 --> 00:13:06.100
from that we see, say, a fly wing.

00:13:06.100 --> 00:13:08.090
That this is somehow
a different structure.

00:13:08.090 --> 00:13:10.760
It's not the same, even
though it's a wing,

00:13:10.760 --> 00:13:13.250
just like a bird wing, but it's
composed of different bones.

00:13:13.250 --> 00:13:16.150
It's essentially a different design.

00:13:16.150 --> 00:13:18.200
Now, Owen was not an
evolutionary biologist.

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:20.537
And so, just like I'm dancing
around the word history

00:13:20.537 --> 00:13:21.960
and evolution and so forth,

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:24.300
Owen spent this whole book
on the nature of limbs

00:13:24.300 --> 00:13:26.820
dancing around the concept as well.

00:13:26.820 --> 00:13:28.620
Now, this whole notion
was actually a hot topic

00:13:28.620 --> 00:13:29.513
for a long time.

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:32.580
This pattern of similarity was identified

00:13:32.580 --> 00:13:35.570
by people beginning in
the 1600's (mumbles).

00:13:35.570 --> 00:13:40.540
One of the key players
here preceded Darwin

00:13:40.540 --> 00:13:41.500
by several centuries.

00:13:41.500 --> 00:13:42.950
And this is Saint-Hilaire.

00:13:42.950 --> 00:13:46.010
Saint-Hilaire was a natural
philosopher from France.

00:13:46.010 --> 00:13:48.260
And he looked at the
same pattern, actually,

00:13:48.260 --> 00:13:50.830
several decades before Owen.

00:13:50.830 --> 00:13:52.810
And he came up with a
really wonderful law,

00:13:52.810 --> 00:13:55.990
a natural law, called
the Law of Connections.

00:13:55.990 --> 00:13:57.720
And he was big into laws,

00:13:57.720 --> 00:14:00.020
as a lot of his contemporaries were,

00:14:00.020 --> 00:14:02.350
to try to understand
what are the regularities

00:14:02.350 --> 00:14:04.400
behind the designs of bodies.

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:06.660
And his Law of Connections was, basically,

00:14:06.660 --> 00:14:09.680
that the way bones, the
pattern that bones articulate

00:14:09.680 --> 00:14:12.010
with one another is highly conserved

00:14:12.010 --> 00:14:13.146
among different creatures.

00:14:13.146 --> 00:14:16.030
That's the way you can define sameness.

00:14:16.030 --> 00:14:18.740
And so, he identified this one
bone, two bone, little bone,

00:14:18.740 --> 00:14:22.130
fingers design as a pattern of connections

00:14:22.130 --> 00:14:24.450
that's essentially in variance, okay?

00:14:24.450 --> 00:14:28.230
And that that is the design principle.

00:14:28.230 --> 00:14:30.180
And he extended this throughout the body,

00:14:30.180 --> 00:14:31.857
from the ears and the ear ossicles

00:14:31.857 --> 00:14:34.620
and ribs and the vertebrae and so forth.

00:14:34.620 --> 00:14:35.860
Everything changed

00:14:35.860 --> 00:14:37.580
Saint-Hilaire, Owen's ideas.

00:14:37.580 --> 00:14:40.340
Everything changed with
Charles Darwin, obviously.

00:14:40.340 --> 00:14:42.490
And Charles Darwin saw
this pattern as well,

00:14:42.490 --> 00:14:43.860
and you know, he has this famous quote

00:14:43.860 --> 00:14:44.693
from The Origin of Species,

00:14:44.693 --> 00:14:47.340
"What can be more curious
than the hand of a man,

00:14:47.340 --> 00:14:49.850
formed for grasping, that
of a mole for digging,

00:14:49.850 --> 00:14:51.910
the leg of a horse, the
paddle of the porpoise,

00:14:51.910 --> 00:14:52.950
and the wing of the bat,

00:14:52.950 --> 00:14:55.350
should all be constructed
on the same pattern."

00:14:55.350 --> 00:14:57.400
And what struck Darwin was

00:14:57.400 --> 00:15:01.000
that despite significant variation...

00:15:03.830 --> 00:15:06.210
despite significant variation
and function, right?

00:15:06.210 --> 00:15:07.210
So you have wings.

00:15:07.210 --> 00:15:08.050
You have flippers.

00:15:08.050 --> 00:15:10.770
You have, sort of generalized
forelimbs of different kinds,

00:15:10.770 --> 00:15:13.910
forelimbs for digging
and running and so forth.

00:15:13.910 --> 00:15:17.280
That this one bone, two bone
pattern is sort of the template

00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:18.713
for all this adaptation.

00:15:19.630 --> 00:15:23.040
And it became clear to him
that the functional argument

00:15:23.040 --> 00:15:24.730
for why you have have
this one bone, two bone,

00:15:24.730 --> 00:15:27.590
little bone ray pattern is useless.

00:15:27.590 --> 00:15:29.550
It really only makes sense

00:15:29.550 --> 00:15:31.930
if these creatures evolved
from a common ancestor

00:15:31.930 --> 00:15:34.430
that also had this one bone, two bone,

00:15:34.430 --> 00:15:36.140
little bone ray plan as well.

00:15:36.140 --> 00:15:39.970
So, he explained this
concept that Owen was,

00:15:39.970 --> 00:15:42.830
of sameness that Owen was
dancing around for years,

00:15:42.830 --> 00:15:46.630
and Saint-Hilaire was trying
to develop laws of form for,

00:15:46.630 --> 00:15:49.540
he explained it through
the principle of descent

00:15:49.540 --> 00:15:50.573
with modification.

00:15:51.460 --> 00:15:53.060
And that concept was really powerful

00:15:53.060 --> 00:15:56.250
because what it does is it
enables us to make predictions.

00:15:56.250 --> 00:15:59.590
That we could then say
that if this pattern,

00:15:59.590 --> 00:16:01.580
one bone, two bone, and so forth,

00:16:01.580 --> 00:16:04.500
has a history, we should see
that history in the rocks.

00:16:04.500 --> 00:16:06.880
We should see that history
in comparative anatomy.

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:09.600
It should be written in the
bodies of other animals.

00:16:09.600 --> 00:16:11.290
And that's exactly what Darwin did.

00:16:11.290 --> 00:16:13.410
And he said, you know,
well, I mean, he implied

00:16:13.410 --> 00:16:14.800
that essentially you would see

00:16:14.800 --> 00:16:17.610
that this pattern in other
creatures that don't have limbs.

00:16:17.610 --> 00:16:18.760
What about the fins of fish?

00:16:18.760 --> 00:16:21.990
I'm just showing you a
forelimb of a coelacanth here.

00:16:21.990 --> 00:16:25.190
And indeed when you
layer it in, you see...

00:16:28.910 --> 00:16:30.440
You see the skeleton.

00:16:30.440 --> 00:16:32.010
And again, it has the one bone,

00:16:32.010 --> 00:16:34.130
but only doesn't have the
rest of the pattern as well.

00:16:34.130 --> 00:16:35.910
You should see some, but
not all of that pattern

00:16:35.910 --> 00:16:39.690
as you go deeper in the
evolutionary tree, if you will.

00:16:39.690 --> 00:16:41.310
And it's those predictions
I've spent my time

00:16:41.310 --> 00:16:43.770
as a paleontologist trying to look at,

00:16:43.770 --> 00:16:45.240
to see the assembly of this pattern,

00:16:45.240 --> 00:16:47.020
the one bone, two bone
pattern and so forth,

00:16:47.020 --> 00:16:49.147
by finding fossils, looking
at genes and development,

00:16:49.147 --> 00:16:50.290
and so forth.

00:16:50.290 --> 00:16:54.720
And indeed, when you look at
Devonian Age limbed animals,

00:16:54.720 --> 00:16:56.580
from about 365 million years ago.

00:16:56.580 --> 00:16:58.140
This one's backwards, sorry about that.

00:16:58.140 --> 00:16:59.430
But you see the one bone, two bone,

00:16:59.430 --> 00:17:02.380
little bone, finger program already set up

00:17:02.380 --> 00:17:03.930
in the earliest limbed animals.

00:17:03.930 --> 00:17:07.230
And as we look their finned
relatives in the fossil record,

00:17:07.230 --> 00:17:09.410
things like Tiktaalik
and the other creatures

00:17:09.410 --> 00:17:12.260
in the evolutionary tree,
more distant and so forth,

00:17:12.260 --> 00:17:14.653
we begin to see the
assembly of this pattern.

00:17:16.100 --> 00:17:18.340
So, here's a early limbed animal,

00:17:18.340 --> 00:17:20.770
and then you have the other
creatures on the tree,

00:17:20.770 --> 00:17:23.470
each one further away or
more distantly related

00:17:23.470 --> 00:17:25.290
to the limbed animals,

00:17:25.290 --> 00:17:26.520
Where you see an early limbed animal here,

00:17:26.520 --> 00:17:29.440
it has the one bone, two
bone, finger pattern.

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:31.200
Tiktaalik has one bone, two bones,

00:17:31.200 --> 00:17:32.320
has other more distal bones,

00:17:32.320 --> 00:17:35.250
which we can actually compare
in some ways to this cohort.

00:17:35.250 --> 00:17:37.870
And as you go deeper and
deeper and deeper in the tree,

00:17:37.870 --> 00:17:39.830
what you still see is
this one bone, two bone,

00:17:39.830 --> 00:17:43.410
little bone ray pattern
already set up in fish fins

00:17:43.410 --> 00:17:46.290
doing a diversity of things
early in the radiation

00:17:46.290 --> 00:17:49.383
of these kinds of fish,
in fins, with fin webbing.

00:17:51.740 --> 00:17:53.880
And it turns out the
fossils are very useful

00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:55.940
for us to understand
and trace this pattern

00:17:55.940 --> 00:17:59.290
and its adaptive
diversity in the Devonian.

00:17:59.290 --> 00:18:01.510
Things get less sure as we begin

00:18:01.510 --> 00:18:04.340
to look at extant or recent fish.

00:18:04.340 --> 00:18:06.610
So, here you have a fin of a lungfish.

00:18:06.610 --> 00:18:10.050
Here you have fins of paddlefish
and sharks and so forth.

00:18:10.050 --> 00:18:12.820
And when you see what
appears to be a very big gap

00:18:12.820 --> 00:18:16.420
between extant limbs and extant fins,

00:18:16.420 --> 00:18:19.810
although, as you get into
lungfish, no surprise,

00:18:19.810 --> 00:18:21.330
you start to have one bone at the base,

00:18:21.330 --> 00:18:22.800
just like all these other creatures,

00:18:22.800 --> 00:18:24.690
as opposed to many bones at the base

00:18:24.690 --> 00:18:27.693
like other fish more deeply,
more distant in the tree.

00:18:28.560 --> 00:18:30.830
So, we can actually begin
as comparative anatomists

00:18:30.830 --> 00:18:33.150
and so forth, to begin
to really understand

00:18:33.150 --> 00:18:37.030
what happens to the same
appendage in different creatures,

00:18:37.030 --> 00:18:41.600
and for better and worse,
we can make some hypotheses

00:18:41.600 --> 00:18:44.210
about what is the same bone
in different creatures.

00:18:44.210 --> 00:18:45.790
This one bone is the same bone

00:18:45.790 --> 00:18:47.030
in all these different creatures.

00:18:47.030 --> 00:18:48.630
And then, it gets a little tenuous

00:18:48.630 --> 00:18:50.510
as we go further out in the fin,

00:18:50.510 --> 00:18:53.150
but we can still do this to
different degrees of accuracy

00:18:53.150 --> 00:18:55.210
using different kinds of fossils.

00:18:55.210 --> 00:18:56.230
Now, when we talk about sameness,

00:18:56.230 --> 00:18:57.589
I sort of want to introduce the concept,

00:18:57.589 --> 00:18:59.820
and I'm left with some no real analogies,

00:18:59.820 --> 00:19:01.365
and so I just sort of made one up.

00:19:01.365 --> 00:19:05.680
(chuckles) When I was
thinking about this...

00:19:05.680 --> 00:19:07.600
And when you think about,
you know, an organ,

00:19:07.600 --> 00:19:09.770
an organ has parts, and then an organ

00:19:09.770 --> 00:19:12.770
also has processes that make those parts.

00:19:12.770 --> 00:19:14.780
So, you can think about the same thing

00:19:14.780 --> 00:19:17.300
at many different sort
of hierarchical levels,

00:19:17.300 --> 00:19:19.120
so that you can think about the model,

00:19:19.120 --> 00:19:22.300
this sort of obnoxious
car here, a Hummer, right?

00:19:22.300 --> 00:19:26.040
And you can trace the history
of the car, the Hummer,

00:19:26.040 --> 00:19:29.160
over time from small sort of obnoxious car

00:19:29.160 --> 00:19:30.410
to big obnoxious car

00:19:30.410 --> 00:19:33.990
to sort of smaller
Recession-time obnoxious car.

00:19:33.990 --> 00:19:38.300
And then you can dissemble it
into its pieces, its parts,

00:19:38.300 --> 00:19:39.530
which also have a history.

00:19:39.530 --> 00:19:43.950
The tires have a history of
processes that are behind them.

00:19:43.950 --> 00:19:46.850
The windshield, the lights,
the windshield wipers,

00:19:46.850 --> 00:19:49.090
and so forth, all have histories.

00:19:49.090 --> 00:19:51.007
So, you can think of the sameness

00:19:51.007 --> 00:19:54.090
and the history of the
whole entity, the car,

00:19:54.090 --> 00:19:55.157
the Hummer in this case,

00:19:55.157 --> 00:19:56.757
and you can think of the sameness

00:19:56.757 --> 00:20:00.110
and the history of the parts
that make it up as well.

00:20:00.110 --> 00:20:02.480
But you can also think of
the history of the processes

00:20:02.480 --> 00:20:04.690
that make these parts, the vulcanization,

00:20:04.690 --> 00:20:06.520
the processes behind
the making of the rubber

00:20:06.520 --> 00:20:08.620
and the steel and so forth.

00:20:08.620 --> 00:20:11.720
So, you can think about this
at many different levels,

00:20:11.720 --> 00:20:14.380
and each level has explanatory power.

00:20:14.380 --> 00:20:18.330
Indeed, a Hummer and
a Prius appear to have

00:20:18.330 --> 00:20:20.730
very little in common, yet at the level

00:20:20.730 --> 00:20:24.194
of the processes that make the car,

00:20:24.194 --> 00:20:25.940
the tires and so forth,

00:20:25.940 --> 00:20:27.560
they share quite a bit.

00:20:27.560 --> 00:20:30.400
And so, essentially, I want
to look at organs in that way.

00:20:30.400 --> 00:20:31.920
I don't want to push the analogy too far

00:20:31.920 --> 00:20:34.030
'cause like all analogies, it's limited.

00:20:34.030 --> 00:20:36.410
But when you think about a
limb with a skeleton inside,

00:20:36.410 --> 00:20:40.850
you can ask about the limb and
the history and the sameness

00:20:40.850 --> 00:20:43.430
inside this organ, the
pattern of bones here,

00:20:43.430 --> 00:20:47.420
Saint-Hilaire and Owen
and Darwin's pattern,

00:20:47.420 --> 00:20:50.560
you can ask about its parts,
the bone and the cartilage,

00:20:50.560 --> 00:20:52.360
and then you can also, on top of that,

00:20:52.360 --> 00:20:57.330
ask about the sameness and
the history of the toolkit,

00:20:57.330 --> 00:21:00.050
of the biological recipe and processes

00:21:00.050 --> 00:21:02.650
that build these structures
in different creatures.

00:21:02.650 --> 00:21:05.550
And it's really kind of
linking these different levels

00:21:05.550 --> 00:21:08.893
that we're gonna spend our
time today on in the talk.

00:21:10.470 --> 00:21:13.440
So, I want to do is spend some
time on this toolkit issue.

00:21:13.440 --> 00:21:15.390
And to do that, we're really
gonna focus a little bit

00:21:15.390 --> 00:21:17.860
on limb development, and how it arises.

00:21:17.860 --> 00:21:19.200
You know, you think about development.

00:21:19.200 --> 00:21:22.210
It's one of the most wonderful
problems in all of biology.

00:21:22.210 --> 00:21:24.060
You begin as a single-celled egg.

00:21:24.060 --> 00:21:26.370
You end up as a two trillion cell adult.

00:21:26.370 --> 00:21:27.580
Well, a nine trillion cell adult,

00:21:27.580 --> 00:21:29.510
only two trillion of them are yours.

00:21:29.510 --> 00:21:34.233
The other seven trillion are
microbes that inhabit you.

00:21:35.200 --> 00:21:37.070
But over time, that one cell

00:21:37.070 --> 00:21:40.320
becomes a very precisely packed organism

00:21:40.320 --> 00:21:42.030
with the cells packed in the right way,

00:21:42.030 --> 00:21:44.510
differentiated cells doing
their jobs in different ways.

00:21:44.510 --> 00:21:48.210
And much of this development
is written inside the DNA

00:21:48.210 --> 00:21:50.510
that exists within the egg

00:21:50.510 --> 00:21:52.660
and its interaction with
the environment around it,

00:21:52.660 --> 00:21:55.630
as well as the internal
environment in the embryo.

00:21:55.630 --> 00:21:56.750
One of the outcomes of that is actually

00:21:56.750 --> 00:21:59.020
we can watch development
happen as things get bigger

00:21:59.020 --> 00:22:01.730
and more complicated and
differentiated over time.

00:22:01.730 --> 00:22:03.980
And the limb is no different.

00:22:03.980 --> 00:22:06.930
So, limbs begin as little
pouches out the side of the body.

00:22:08.100 --> 00:22:09.970
And over time, they grow out.

00:22:09.970 --> 00:22:11.840
And as they grow out and
extend out of the body,

00:22:11.840 --> 00:22:13.607
it's called a limb bud at this stage,

00:22:13.607 --> 00:22:15.010
'cause it's a limb and it's a bud,

00:22:15.010 --> 00:22:16.450
and it comes out of the body.

00:22:16.450 --> 00:22:18.520
And inside the limb bud cells go

00:22:18.520 --> 00:22:21.410
from kind of looking all
alike to differentiating.

00:22:21.410 --> 00:22:23.100
You start to see cartilage cells

00:22:23.100 --> 00:22:24.840
and, eventually, muscle cells,

00:22:24.840 --> 00:22:27.710
and the cartilage differentiating,
develops into bone,

00:22:27.710 --> 00:22:28.790
and this good stuff.

00:22:28.790 --> 00:22:31.700
And you could watch over time
the formation of the pattern

00:22:31.700 --> 00:22:36.490
as the limb bud grows out.

00:22:36.490 --> 00:22:39.460
Now, underneath this,
controlling this in many ways,

00:22:39.460 --> 00:22:42.740
are a series of events that are
sort of written in the genes

00:22:42.740 --> 00:22:43.720
if you will.

00:22:43.720 --> 00:22:45.670
And here I have a limb bud

00:22:45.670 --> 00:22:47.730
showing you some of the
main signaling centers

00:22:47.730 --> 00:22:49.260
that if you were to open a text book

00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:51.520
in developmental biology,

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:52.920
or actually, introduction to biology

00:22:52.920 --> 00:22:54.660
that you see, and this is a limb bud

00:22:54.660 --> 00:22:56.310
with two patches of tissue

00:22:56.310 --> 00:22:58.550
that are known as signaling
centers, more or less.

00:22:58.550 --> 00:23:02.680
And what they do is, their
behavior actually promotes

00:23:02.680 --> 00:23:05.210
and patterns the limb in many ways.

00:23:05.210 --> 00:23:07.170
Now, there are factors
that exist in the body

00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:09.140
that actually set these
things up initially,

00:23:09.140 --> 00:23:10.280
early in development.

00:23:10.280 --> 00:23:11.490
But then once they're set up,

00:23:11.490 --> 00:23:13.420
they're really major properties

00:23:13.420 --> 00:23:17.880
of how the appendage grows and
forms in early development.

00:23:17.880 --> 00:23:21.210
And one thing that underlies
it, is a series of genes

00:23:21.210 --> 00:23:23.740
that are turned on, and
we can actually map those

00:23:23.740 --> 00:23:26.620
with a variety of techniques
to see their activity,

00:23:26.620 --> 00:23:28.610
and look to see the chain of events

00:23:28.610 --> 00:23:33.450
by which these two
patches, the AER up here,

00:23:33.450 --> 00:23:34.370
and the ZPA here,

00:23:34.370 --> 00:23:39.190
I'm just gonna use their
abbreviations to talk about them.

00:23:39.190 --> 00:23:41.230
And then there series
of genes that interact.

00:23:41.230 --> 00:23:43.710
So, in the ZPA, there's a prominent gene

00:23:43.710 --> 00:23:46.390
that marks ZPA activity
called Sonic hedgehog,

00:23:46.390 --> 00:23:48.190
here shown as SHH .

00:23:48.190 --> 00:23:51.710
And in the AER, there
are genes known as FGF's.

00:23:51.710 --> 00:23:54.510
FGF8 is a real prominent one.

00:23:54.510 --> 00:23:55.590
And let me just go into these,

00:23:55.590 --> 00:23:57.030
and just talk a little bit about them

00:23:57.030 --> 00:23:59.740
'cause they're gonna be our
road map to look at sameness

00:23:59.740 --> 00:24:03.780
in a variety of different
limbed and non-limbed animals.

00:24:03.780 --> 00:24:05.040
So, if you look at a embryo.

00:24:05.040 --> 00:24:06.190
Here's a embryo early in development.

00:24:06.190 --> 00:24:07.310
It's a chick embryo,

00:24:07.310 --> 00:24:10.860
and it's stained with one of
these called dyes, if you will,

00:24:10.860 --> 00:24:12.670
and what it does, is
this is attached to FGF8.

00:24:12.670 --> 00:24:15.660
So it's a marker for the AER, okay?

00:24:15.660 --> 00:24:16.767
And you could look at the AER here,

00:24:16.767 --> 00:24:20.130
and it's where this
gene FGF8 is turned on.

00:24:20.130 --> 00:24:21.790
It's turned on no where
else in the fin bud,

00:24:21.790 --> 00:24:23.080
that's signature of that.

00:24:23.080 --> 00:24:25.210
And when you pop this
thing under a microscope,

00:24:25.210 --> 00:24:27.250
what you see is, it has a ridge there.

00:24:27.250 --> 00:24:29.160
It's a ridge of tissue, and you see,

00:24:29.160 --> 00:24:30.960
if you ever cut this as a section,

00:24:30.960 --> 00:24:32.680
this is what that section would like.

00:24:32.680 --> 00:24:34.410
And it's a thickened ridge of sort of

00:24:34.410 --> 00:24:37.150
epithelial-cut type cells separated

00:24:37.150 --> 00:24:40.720
from sort of more disorganized
cells in the center.

00:24:40.720 --> 00:24:42.100
And it has special properties,

00:24:42.100 --> 00:24:43.330
and those properties are really important

00:24:43.330 --> 00:24:45.870
for our stor because
when it has a property

00:24:45.870 --> 00:24:49.900
such that it seems to promote
the growth of the appendage,

00:24:49.900 --> 00:24:53.020
so that if you remove the
AER early in development,

00:24:53.020 --> 00:24:55.560
say at stage 18 here,
you're left with a limb

00:24:55.560 --> 00:24:57.060
with only a humerus.

00:24:57.060 --> 00:24:59.530
If you remove the AER at
a slightly later stage,

00:24:59.530 --> 00:25:02.980
say at stage 20, you're left with a limb

00:25:02.980 --> 00:25:05.390
that has a humerus and
part of a radius and ulna.

00:25:05.390 --> 00:25:07.843
And so, you're left with
more at the later stage

00:25:07.843 --> 00:25:09.900
that you remove the AER.

00:25:09.900 --> 00:25:12.310
It clearly promotes the
growth of the appendage

00:25:12.310 --> 00:25:13.730
in a lot of ways.

00:25:13.730 --> 00:25:15.500
And so, that's a stage-specific effect.

00:25:15.500 --> 00:25:17.850
So, the AER is very
important in that regard.

00:25:17.850 --> 00:25:20.820
There's another one, and that's the ZPA.

00:25:20.820 --> 00:25:22.610
Remember we talked about the ZPA?

00:25:22.610 --> 00:25:25.370
And it had that gene Sonic
hedgehog, the SHH gene.

00:25:25.370 --> 00:25:27.540
This is another chick embryo,

00:25:27.540 --> 00:25:28.383
and what you could see here is,

00:25:28.383 --> 00:25:30.930
here is a Sonic hedgehog
that's been stained there.

00:25:30.930 --> 00:25:32.170
It's also been stained with FGF8,

00:25:32.170 --> 00:25:35.870
so you see the AER here,
and there's the ZPA.

00:25:35.870 --> 00:25:37.310
Now, the ZPA seems to be involved

00:25:37.310 --> 00:25:39.600
with a lot of events across the body.

00:25:39.600 --> 00:25:42.360
In the appendage, it
also has a lot of events

00:25:42.360 --> 00:25:43.760
that are associated with it.

00:25:43.760 --> 00:25:46.060
But one of the real prominent
effects with the ZPA

00:25:46.060 --> 00:25:49.620
and Sonic hedgehog lies
in the differentiation

00:25:49.620 --> 00:25:51.470
of the digits, the fingers.

00:25:51.470 --> 00:25:52.303
Because if you look,

00:25:52.303 --> 00:25:55.360
what you can do is you
can take the ZPA tissue,

00:25:55.360 --> 00:25:56.780
you can dissect it out,

00:25:56.780 --> 00:25:59.980
and you can pop it on the
other side of the appendage.

00:25:59.980 --> 00:26:02.540
When you do, you get a
very characteristic effect.

00:26:02.540 --> 00:26:04.350
And you could also get the same effect

00:26:04.350 --> 00:26:05.870
when you cause Sonic hedgehog,

00:26:05.870 --> 00:26:07.870
the gene that is turned on here,

00:26:07.870 --> 00:26:10.990
to be expressed on the
opposite side, ectopically,

00:26:10.990 --> 00:26:12.810
misexpressed on the other side.

00:26:12.810 --> 00:26:15.300
So, you could do all this surgically,

00:26:15.300 --> 00:26:17.540
or you can actually implant a bead

00:26:17.540 --> 00:26:20.730
of a compound known as retinoic
acid, form of vitamin A,

00:26:20.730 --> 00:26:24.200
which will induce another patch
of Sonic hedgehog activity.

00:26:24.200 --> 00:26:26.450
So, normal would only have
Sonic hedgehog in the ZPA,

00:26:26.450 --> 00:26:28.230
which is the normal ZPA here,

00:26:28.230 --> 00:26:32.380
but you can induce another
ZPA, an ectopic one,

00:26:32.380 --> 00:26:34.110
through this bead of retinoic acid.

00:26:34.110 --> 00:26:35.450
And voila, what you get?

00:26:35.450 --> 00:26:38.333
You get a mirror image
duplication of the fingers,

00:26:39.400 --> 00:26:41.420
okay, in a variety of different species.

00:26:41.420 --> 00:26:44.190
And if you knock down,
if you sort of inhibit

00:26:44.190 --> 00:26:47.260
Sonic hedgehog expression, or
take out the ZPA in some ways,

00:26:47.260 --> 00:26:49.270
you reduce the number of fingers.

00:26:49.270 --> 00:26:52.750
So it seems to be the
specification of the fingers

00:26:52.750 --> 00:26:56.020
as you go from the
pinky to the thumb side.

00:26:56.020 --> 00:26:58.920
It really depends on
the activity of the ZPA.

00:26:58.920 --> 00:27:00.670
So, we really have these two centers,

00:27:00.670 --> 00:27:02.690
the AER and the ZPA,

00:27:02.690 --> 00:27:06.370
this is a good part of the
toolkit that builds appendages.

00:27:06.370 --> 00:27:08.660
Now, why am I going into all this?

00:27:08.660 --> 00:27:09.493
Good question.

00:27:10.500 --> 00:27:12.080
Well, it's a useful question to ask,

00:27:12.080 --> 00:27:14.720
given light of our Hummer
analogy I showed you earlier.

00:27:14.720 --> 00:27:16.070
And that is the notion that,

00:27:16.070 --> 00:27:17.940
what's the sameness of the toolkit?

00:27:17.940 --> 00:27:19.330
We could trace the bones.

00:27:19.330 --> 00:27:20.830
What about the toolkit itself?

00:27:21.830 --> 00:27:23.710
So, the idea here, what
we have to do here is

00:27:23.710 --> 00:27:26.330
to look at the toolkit,
the AER and the ZPA,

00:27:26.330 --> 00:27:29.760
and ask the question, what
are they doing in fins?

00:27:29.760 --> 00:27:31.723
And if we choose our creatures right,

00:27:32.580 --> 00:27:34.147
we could begin to come to get,

00:27:34.147 --> 00:27:35.940
and these are the fins of these creatures,

00:27:35.940 --> 00:27:39.580
and we do it along a
phylogenetic evolutionary tree,

00:27:39.580 --> 00:27:42.900
mapping with Chondrichthyans
here, sharks, skates, and rays,

00:27:42.900 --> 00:27:44.900
Actinopterygns, which are ray-finned fish

00:27:44.900 --> 00:27:48.160
like paddlefish and teleost and so forth,

00:27:48.160 --> 00:27:49.570
and look at limbed animals.

00:27:49.570 --> 00:27:51.660
We could begin to ask the question is,

00:27:51.660 --> 00:27:53.170
how ancient is the toolkit?

00:27:53.170 --> 00:27:55.100
Is it the same thing in fins and limbs?

00:27:55.100 --> 00:27:56.950
Is it doing similar kinds of things?

00:27:56.950 --> 00:27:58.970
Are genes doing the
similar kinds of things?

00:27:58.970 --> 00:28:00.620
And this is another way of asking

00:28:00.620 --> 00:28:02.790
how these organs came about.

00:28:02.790 --> 00:28:04.770
So, what we've been doing in
my lab is looking at fish,

00:28:04.770 --> 00:28:06.490
and most lately, we've
been looking at sharks,

00:28:06.490 --> 00:28:09.770
not Great Whites, but we've
been looking at skates, ratfish,

00:28:09.770 --> 00:28:12.680
the three major groups:
skates, ratfish, and sharks.

00:28:12.680 --> 00:28:14.630
It's a challenge working
with some of these creatures.

00:28:14.630 --> 00:28:18.010
It's not like you can buy
shark embryos at the store.

00:28:18.010 --> 00:28:21.290
What we get them from is the
Shedd Aquarium in Chicago.

00:28:21.290 --> 00:28:23.650
We also get them from the
Marine Biological Laboratories

00:28:23.650 --> 00:28:24.650
in Wood's Hole,

00:28:24.650 --> 00:28:27.600
what provides us a supply of
about 20 or 30 eggs a month.

00:28:27.600 --> 00:28:29.840
Not a whole lot to do embryology on,

00:28:29.840 --> 00:28:32.030
but enough for our purposes.

00:28:32.030 --> 00:28:34.770
This all began, really, in my laboratory

00:28:35.790 --> 00:28:38.390
with a post-doc by the name of Randy Don.

00:28:38.390 --> 00:28:40.730
Randy worked on chicken eggs for his PhD,

00:28:40.730 --> 00:28:42.180
looking at limb development.

00:28:42.180 --> 00:28:43.330
And when he looked at shark eggs,

00:28:43.330 --> 00:28:44.780
he saw that they looked
a lot like chickens.

00:28:44.780 --> 00:28:47.200
So, we decided to all the
experiments he did on chickens,

00:28:47.200 --> 00:28:49.350
only on sharks and skates.

00:28:49.350 --> 00:28:50.820
So, this is a wonderful comparative test

00:28:50.820 --> 00:28:52.100
to see how they lie together.

00:28:52.100 --> 00:28:52.933
One of the things you'll see is

00:28:52.933 --> 00:28:55.300
every time I show a molecular
biologist from my lab,

00:28:55.300 --> 00:28:57.850
in this talk, they're in the
field collecting fossils.

00:28:57.850 --> 00:28:59.450
So, I want you to know
that molecular biologists

00:28:59.450 --> 00:29:01.050
make very good fossil finders.

00:29:01.050 --> 00:29:03.333
So, there's hope for those
of you, you guys yet.

00:29:03.333 --> 00:29:06.670
(chuckles) Alright, sorry about that.

00:29:06.670 --> 00:29:08.730
Anyway so, you can ask questions.

00:29:08.730 --> 00:29:09.807
There's AER in limbs, here it is.

00:29:09.807 --> 00:29:11.300
And you can see the section here,

00:29:11.300 --> 00:29:14.410
and here is the FGF8 expression.

00:29:14.410 --> 00:29:16.093
You look in shark fins,
and what you see is,

00:29:16.093 --> 00:29:18.120
in a skate in this case, Chondrichthyan,

00:29:18.120 --> 00:29:22.339
there's the FGF8 expression,
and you also have an AER.

00:29:22.339 --> 00:29:23.172
And in fact, you have an AER,

00:29:23.172 --> 00:29:24.100
and it actually gets long

00:29:24.100 --> 00:29:26.800
and turns into another
structure called a AEF,

00:29:26.800 --> 00:29:29.640
which is related to fin formation.

00:29:29.640 --> 00:29:31.110
So, it has the AER and that seems,

00:29:31.110 --> 00:29:32.740
and it's also in all fish fins,

00:29:32.740 --> 00:29:34.210
and so what you have is we can trace this

00:29:34.210 --> 00:29:36.330
as the same structure all the way through.

00:29:36.330 --> 00:29:37.163
Then what about the ZPA?

00:29:37.163 --> 00:29:38.840
'Cause you remember the ZPA has

00:29:38.840 --> 00:29:40.860
this Sonic hedgehog expression here.

00:29:40.860 --> 00:29:43.060
And when we misexpress
it with retinoic acid,

00:29:43.060 --> 00:29:45.220
we get these duplicated structures.

00:29:45.220 --> 00:29:47.980
So for this, we look at
the eggs of these things.

00:29:47.980 --> 00:29:50.270
And so, here you see the yolk of a skate,

00:29:50.270 --> 00:29:52.700
and there's the embryo on top of the yolk.

00:29:52.700 --> 00:29:54.990
They develop inside an egg case.

00:29:54.990 --> 00:29:57.490
Here's a shark, again with the embryo.

00:29:57.490 --> 00:29:59.210
And you can treat these things

00:29:59.210 --> 00:30:02.617
by injecting retinoic acid.

00:30:02.617 --> 00:30:04.230
And this took a while to figure out,

00:30:04.230 --> 00:30:05.470
of different concentrations,

00:30:05.470 --> 00:30:07.500
into the egg at different stages,

00:30:07.500 --> 00:30:08.560
and to see what it does.

00:30:08.560 --> 00:30:10.320
Because in this chick what it'll do,

00:30:10.320 --> 00:30:14.080
is induce that ectopic AER
with the Sonic expression,

00:30:14.080 --> 00:30:15.920
and you'll get duplicated digits.

00:30:15.920 --> 00:30:19.360
In sharks, here's the normal,

00:30:19.360 --> 00:30:23.750
where you have the expression
of the Sonic hedgehog

00:30:23.750 --> 00:30:25.670
in the posteriorum margin of the fin.

00:30:25.670 --> 00:30:26.680
Just like in a limb.

00:30:26.680 --> 00:30:29.120
So, the expression, the activity
of the gene is the same.

00:30:29.120 --> 00:30:31.010
And when you treat it
with this retinoic acid,

00:30:31.010 --> 00:30:33.300
you turn it on, you turn
it on all the way distally,

00:30:33.300 --> 00:30:35.700
and then you also turn it on
on the anterior end as well.

00:30:35.700 --> 00:30:40.000
So, you induce expression in novel places,

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:42.130
particularly in the anterior end.

00:30:42.130 --> 00:30:45.110
You can ask what the anatomical
readout of all this is.

00:30:45.110 --> 00:30:47.030
Here's a dorsal fin, and
you can see a dorsal fin.

00:30:47.030 --> 00:30:48.800
This is the normal one, untreated.

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:51.260
And you could see it has, the
cartilage is stained blue,

00:30:51.260 --> 00:30:54.170
and you could see it has,
like, little stubs here.

00:30:54.170 --> 00:30:58.400
That's the axis of the fin, and
off of this come these rays.

00:30:58.400 --> 00:31:00.710
When we treat it with retinoic
acid, more often than not,

00:31:00.710 --> 00:31:03.240
we find, voila, a mirror
image duplication.

00:31:03.240 --> 00:31:04.890
That is, you end up with
an axis here, an axis here,

00:31:04.890 --> 00:31:06.460
and rays coming off of either side.

00:31:06.460 --> 00:31:09.230
And these axes can take, these
mirror-image duplications,

00:31:09.230 --> 00:31:10.840
can take different forms.

00:31:10.840 --> 00:31:12.957
But again, in chicks
and in Chondrichthyans,

00:31:12.957 --> 00:31:15.513
and in not showing you, but
also in other kinds of fish,

00:31:15.513 --> 00:31:16.940
what do we find?

00:31:16.940 --> 00:31:21.780
We find a great continuity of
big portions of the toolkit

00:31:21.780 --> 00:31:23.880
that make fins and limbs.

00:31:23.880 --> 00:31:26.770
AER, ZPA, and I'm not even
showing you all the other genes

00:31:26.770 --> 00:31:30.380
in that cascade, that are
involved in this formation.

00:31:30.380 --> 00:31:32.360
So, the beautiful thing here
is when we find it in a lot

00:31:32.360 --> 00:31:34.320
of these groups here,
we could begin to say

00:31:34.320 --> 00:31:37.180
that this genetic
toolkit is the same thing

00:31:37.180 --> 00:31:38.580
in all these creatures,

00:31:38.580 --> 00:31:40.870
and we can begin to say
that it was a property

00:31:40.870 --> 00:31:44.613
of the common ancestor of
all fish with appendages.

00:31:46.430 --> 00:31:48.160
Now, how do you begin
to approach the question

00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:49.960
of comparing this to creatures

00:31:49.960 --> 00:31:51.400
that don't have appendages at all?

00:31:51.400 --> 00:31:53.749
So, appendages had to come into being

00:31:53.749 --> 00:31:57.120
at some point in evolutionary history.

00:31:57.120 --> 00:31:57.953
And for this, what we begin to use

00:31:57.953 --> 00:31:59.990
is one of Owen's notions,

00:31:59.990 --> 00:32:03.443
that is, to look at the
repeated parts in the body.

00:32:04.510 --> 00:32:06.896
And this is Vesalius
showing the human skeleton,

00:32:06.896 --> 00:32:08.558
and what you see here is
a hindlimb and a forelimb.

00:32:08.558 --> 00:32:09.760
And you could see there's lots of

00:32:09.760 --> 00:32:10.910
repeated parts in the body.

00:32:10.910 --> 00:32:11.970
There's repeated vertebrae.

00:32:11.970 --> 00:32:13.450
There's repeated ribs.

00:32:13.450 --> 00:32:16.800
There's repeated appendages
between forelimb and hindlimb.

00:32:16.800 --> 00:32:19.650
Lots of repeated parts in the body.

00:32:19.650 --> 00:32:21.890
To Owen, this was really
significant because what he did,

00:32:21.890 --> 00:32:24.480
even though he wasn't an
evolutionary biologist,

00:32:24.480 --> 00:32:26.860
what he did was he showed he had an idea

00:32:26.860 --> 00:32:30.110
that all this diversity that
we see here in these bodies

00:32:30.110 --> 00:32:32.530
with all these repeated parts

00:32:32.530 --> 00:32:35.120
can be traced with something
he called an archetype,

00:32:35.120 --> 00:32:38.130
which was a philosophical ideal.

00:32:38.130 --> 00:32:41.320
This little thing here that
does not exist in nature, okay?

00:32:41.320 --> 00:32:44.360
But to Owen, it was the sort of thing

00:32:44.360 --> 00:32:48.110
that all vertebrate animals
diversity is derived from.

00:32:48.110 --> 00:32:51.640
It basically consisted of
a series of repeated parts,

00:32:51.640 --> 00:32:54.910
of the vertebrae, and
the ribs, and so forth.

00:32:54.910 --> 00:32:57.540
And that the appendages
and the jaws and the heads

00:32:57.540 --> 00:33:00.210
all come about from the consolidation of

00:33:04.270 --> 00:33:05.880
these repeated parts in different ways

00:33:05.880 --> 00:33:07.570
to make different appendages.

00:33:07.570 --> 00:33:09.860
This is a very attractive idea
to comparative anatomists,

00:33:09.860 --> 00:33:11.960
and actually to developmental
biologists as well.

00:33:11.960 --> 00:33:14.440
Let's just take a peak at a fossil shark.

00:33:14.440 --> 00:33:17.172
And I'll just show you how
we've been approaching it.

00:33:17.172 --> 00:33:19.180
And here's a shark known as Enneacanthus.

00:33:19.180 --> 00:33:22.340
It's a fossil shark, and you
could see the appendages here,

00:33:22.340 --> 00:33:25.120
and ribs and so forth.

00:33:25.120 --> 00:33:27.350
And what really sort of
caught a lot of people's eye,

00:33:27.350 --> 00:33:28.680
and I'll show you one of the people

00:33:28.680 --> 00:33:32.120
who's very important in a
second, is this area here.

00:33:32.120 --> 00:33:33.170
'Cause look at the repeated parts.

00:33:33.170 --> 00:33:34.570
Here is the gill skeleton.

00:33:34.570 --> 00:33:36.300
This is the upper and lower jaw.

00:33:36.300 --> 00:33:37.740
And then you have the gill structures,

00:33:37.740 --> 00:33:39.380
and you see they form these little hoops.

00:33:39.380 --> 00:33:41.790
And doesn't it seem, and
this is the shoulder here,

00:33:41.790 --> 00:33:44.470
and the fin, doesn't it
seem like the shoulder

00:33:44.470 --> 00:33:47.382
is a repeated part of the gill structure,

00:33:47.382 --> 00:33:49.682
the structures that
support the gill skeleton?

00:33:53.750 --> 00:33:54.840
The study of these gill arches

00:33:54.840 --> 00:33:56.570
has been very, very, very important

00:33:56.570 --> 00:33:57.860
in understanding anatomy.

00:33:57.860 --> 00:33:59.620
'Cause what you see is, let's
just look at the front end

00:33:59.620 --> 00:34:00.660
in these repeated structures.

00:34:00.660 --> 00:34:02.330
I'm not including the shoulder here.

00:34:02.330 --> 00:34:04.670
What you have is several
different gill arches.

00:34:04.670 --> 00:34:06.600
There's the first arch,
which is the jaw arch,

00:34:06.600 --> 00:34:08.030
which I've colored in here,

00:34:08.030 --> 00:34:09.810
which is the upper and lower jaws.

00:34:09.810 --> 00:34:12.770
There's the second arch,
which is the hyoid arch,

00:34:12.770 --> 00:34:14.720
which consists of this
bone here and another bone.

00:34:14.720 --> 00:34:15.570
This bone is very important.

00:34:15.570 --> 00:34:16.690
It's gonna appear later in the talk.

00:34:16.690 --> 00:34:19.130
So, remember, HM, hyoid mandibula.

00:34:19.130 --> 00:34:22.160
And then you have a series of
these arches, the gill arches,

00:34:22.160 --> 00:34:23.393
which support the gills.

00:34:24.270 --> 00:34:25.730
This really captured the imagination

00:34:25.730 --> 00:34:29.370
of comparative anatomists,
and most famous of these

00:34:29.370 --> 00:34:30.490
is Karl Gegenbaur,

00:34:30.490 --> 00:34:33.950
who is sort of the father of
comparative anatomy in Germany.

00:34:33.950 --> 00:34:35.580
And he came up with a notion

00:34:36.600 --> 00:34:40.040
that basically held,

00:34:40.040 --> 00:34:41.026
and this is the gill skeleton.

00:34:41.026 --> 00:34:42.810
This the mandibular arch.
This is that hyoid arch,

00:34:42.810 --> 00:34:44.230
and these are the gill arches here.

00:34:44.230 --> 00:34:48.140
He basically said is if you
compare these structures,

00:34:48.140 --> 00:34:52.730
the shoulder is the same
thing as these gill arches,

00:34:52.730 --> 00:34:55.980
and the appendage skeleton, the fin,

00:34:55.980 --> 00:34:59.020
is the same things as these rays in blue

00:34:59.020 --> 00:35:00.500
that extend from the gills.

00:35:00.500 --> 00:35:02.510
And he proposed this gill-arch hypothesis

00:35:02.510 --> 00:35:03.770
that everybody laughed at.

00:35:03.770 --> 00:35:04.780
And it was basically the notion,

00:35:04.780 --> 00:35:05.620
he took it one step further.

00:35:05.620 --> 00:35:07.460
He says not only are these the same thing,

00:35:07.460 --> 00:35:11.370
but that fins arose as
being modified gill arches.

00:35:11.370 --> 00:35:14.280
And it was a hypothesis that was almost,

00:35:14.280 --> 00:35:17.063
quickly ignored after it appeared.

