00:38:57.160 --> 00:39:00.450
There's a relationship
between the AER and the ZPA,

00:39:00.450 --> 00:39:01.850
between the genes in them,

00:39:01.850 --> 00:39:03.990
the Sonic hedgehog and FGF8.

00:39:03.990 --> 00:39:05.237
There's all sorts of intermediary genes

00:39:05.237 --> 00:39:06.880
and a feedback loop between them.

00:39:06.880 --> 00:39:08.650
And that feedback loop and all those genes

00:39:08.650 --> 00:39:12.650
are present doing similar
things in the gills,

00:39:12.650 --> 00:39:16.250
and in the gill rays,
and in the appendages.

00:39:16.250 --> 00:39:19.080
So, it really seems at
a developmental level,

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:23.090
that the toolkit that's used
to pattern an appendage,

00:39:23.090 --> 00:39:24.960
the fin, in this case, of a shark,

00:39:24.960 --> 00:39:27.220
is the same toolkit, is the same thing

00:39:27.220 --> 00:39:28.910
as this pattern in the gill rays.

00:39:28.910 --> 00:39:30.690
This is a developmental extension,

00:39:30.690 --> 00:39:33.473
a sort of level of the
mechanisms that make anatomy,

00:39:34.333 --> 00:39:36.660
of Gegenbaur's theory.

00:39:36.660 --> 00:39:38.419
Question really comes
down to how would you know

00:39:38.419 --> 00:39:40.390
if gills actually were transformed

00:39:40.390 --> 00:39:41.660
into these things over time.

00:39:41.660 --> 00:39:43.660
And what we need here are fossils.

00:39:43.660 --> 00:39:45.390
And this is where fossils would tell us

00:39:45.390 --> 00:39:48.650
the sequence of stages in
the transformation, perhaps,

00:39:48.650 --> 00:39:50.300
of gills to rays.

00:39:50.300 --> 00:39:52.490
Right now, what we know is
if you look at jawless fish,

00:39:52.490 --> 00:39:55.640
which don't have appendages,
but have these gill rays.

00:39:55.640 --> 00:39:57.400
Okay, they have a full set of rays

00:39:57.400 --> 00:39:59.723
that are sure very large
in the posterior end.

00:39:59.723 --> 00:40:01.960
They're very well developed.

00:40:01.960 --> 00:40:04.280
Ideally, what we'd like to
find is intermediate stages

00:40:04.280 --> 00:40:05.830
in this process in the fossil record.

00:40:05.830 --> 00:40:08.310
And all someone has to do
is target Silurian age rocks

00:40:08.310 --> 00:40:10.023
to test their hypothesis.

00:40:11.790 --> 00:40:14.506
The other thing about
these gill cartilages

00:40:14.506 --> 00:40:16.670
is they are wonderful for anatomy.

00:40:16.670 --> 00:40:17.930
Here you see the arches again.

00:40:17.930 --> 00:40:20.430
It's the upper jaw and lower jaw.

00:40:20.430 --> 00:40:21.263
It's first arch.

00:40:21.263 --> 00:40:23.690
Here's the hyoid arch with
the hyoid mandibular there,

00:40:23.690 --> 00:40:25.550
and the gill cartilages.

00:40:25.550 --> 00:40:27.680
They all develop within the swellings,

00:40:27.680 --> 00:40:29.500
the branchial arches that develop

00:40:29.500 --> 00:40:30.650
in the front end of the embryo.

00:40:30.650 --> 00:40:32.150
Here's the pair of eyes.

00:40:32.150 --> 00:40:33.500
And you see there's a pair of arches here

00:40:33.500 --> 00:40:34.670
that we colored in.

00:40:34.670 --> 00:40:37.290
If you follow the fates of
the cells that are in there,

00:40:37.290 --> 00:40:39.600
and these cells come
from a variety of places

00:40:39.600 --> 00:40:41.540
as well as develop in situ.

00:40:41.540 --> 00:40:44.910
These cells differentiate
into respective structures

00:40:44.910 --> 00:40:46.310
in the arch.

00:40:46.310 --> 00:40:49.280
You can look at any creature
that has a head, take a human,

00:40:49.280 --> 00:40:50.910
and you see these same branchial arches

00:40:50.910 --> 00:40:54.060
with this first pair, second
pair, third pair, and so forth.

00:40:54.060 --> 00:40:56.360
What happens in a human with these arches,

00:40:56.360 --> 00:40:57.550
they become portions of,

00:40:57.550 --> 00:41:00.170
the first arch becomes a
portion of the lower jaw

00:41:00.170 --> 00:41:02.490
and two bones of our middle ear.

00:41:02.490 --> 00:41:05.670
The second arch becomes a
bone that supports the throat

00:41:05.670 --> 00:41:07.970
and one bone in the middle ear.

00:41:07.970 --> 00:41:10.870
And the others become
portions of the voice box.

00:41:10.870 --> 00:41:13.510
The take-home message here
is that developmentally

00:41:13.510 --> 00:41:15.900
the bones that you're using,

00:41:15.900 --> 00:41:17.140
many of the bones and muscles and nerves

00:41:17.140 --> 00:41:18.727
that your using to hear me with right now,

00:41:18.727 --> 00:41:20.530
and many of the bones
and muscles and nerves,

00:41:20.530 --> 00:41:22.830
or some of them, that I'm using
to talk to with right now,

00:41:22.830 --> 00:41:27.020
correspond to gill structures
developmentally in fish.

00:41:27.020 --> 00:41:28.130
Now, what's interesting about this story,

00:41:28.130 --> 00:41:30.430
and this shows the importance
of integrative biology

00:41:30.430 --> 00:41:32.770
and understanding descent
with modification is,

00:41:32.770 --> 00:41:34.650
okay, you see this in development,

00:41:34.650 --> 00:41:37.380
but in paleontology and the fossil record,

00:41:37.380 --> 00:41:39.380
what I should see is a transformation

00:41:39.380 --> 00:41:43.050
of jaw bones into middle ear bones,

00:41:43.050 --> 00:41:45.420
and a transformation
of a second arch bone,

00:41:45.420 --> 00:41:49.690
namely this hyoid
mandibula into an ear bone.

00:41:49.690 --> 00:41:51.290
And guess what we see.

00:41:51.290 --> 00:41:53.400
When we look at the fossil
record in comparative anatomy,

00:41:53.400 --> 00:41:57.260
what we see is the hyoid
mandibula, the hyoid arch gill bone

00:41:57.260 --> 00:41:59.580
over time it gets smaller
and smaller and smaller,

00:41:59.580 --> 00:42:02.290
such were in Tiktaalik,
which I'm not showing here.

00:42:02.290 --> 00:42:03.620
It's intermediate in condition,

00:42:03.620 --> 00:42:05.850
and then it gradually
shrinks to go into the ear

00:42:05.850 --> 00:42:07.770
to become the stapes.

00:42:07.770 --> 00:42:10.290
Fossils and embryos
showing the same story.

00:42:10.290 --> 00:42:14.390
And what about those jaw bones
that go into the middle ear?

00:42:14.390 --> 00:42:15.223
Same thing.

00:42:15.223 --> 00:42:17.280
If you look at the jaw of
things we call reptiles,

00:42:17.280 --> 00:42:19.020
which have multiple bones in the jaws,

00:42:19.020 --> 00:42:21.020
you can trace two of
these ones in the back.

00:42:21.020 --> 00:42:22.410
They get smaller and smaller and smaller

00:42:22.410 --> 00:42:25.480
'til they translate into the middle ear.

00:42:25.480 --> 00:42:28.130
So, development and fossils are showing us

00:42:28.130 --> 00:42:29.800
the same thing in the ear.

00:42:29.800 --> 00:42:31.370
And it's also showing us
something very important

00:42:31.370 --> 00:42:33.100
about descent with modification

00:42:33.100 --> 00:42:36.466
because the same things
in different creatures,

00:42:36.466 --> 00:42:39.180
if descent with modification is acting,

00:42:39.180 --> 00:42:41.600
the same thing doesn't have
to look like, look like it.

00:42:41.600 --> 00:42:44.110
That is, these middle ear
bones, this stapes here,

00:42:44.110 --> 00:42:46.530
looks nothing like the
hyoid mandibula of a shark.

00:42:46.530 --> 00:42:49.270
Yet it's the same thing
in different creatures.

00:42:49.270 --> 00:42:51.530
These two bones here,
the malleus and incus,

00:42:51.530 --> 00:42:53.070
look nothing like the two bones

00:42:53.070 --> 00:42:56.040
in the back end of one of these jaws.

00:42:56.040 --> 00:42:58.970
Yet it's the same thing
in an evolutionary sense.

00:42:58.970 --> 00:43:01.070
And that's the power of
descent with modification

00:43:01.070 --> 00:43:03.550
because over time, with small changes,

00:43:03.550 --> 00:43:05.150
you can get great differences.

00:43:05.150 --> 00:43:06.590
And we can pick those differences up

00:43:06.590 --> 00:43:08.940
when we look at embryos
and we look at fossils.

00:43:10.090 --> 00:43:12.850
So, the take-home message to
much of what I've been saying

00:43:12.850 --> 00:43:15.800
is that similar biological
recipes make different organs,

00:43:15.800 --> 00:43:18.483
whether it's gills, rays, and appendages.

00:43:19.490 --> 00:43:21.750
And I'll show you some other cases.

00:43:21.750 --> 00:43:23.290
But the important thing,
in terms of thinking

00:43:23.290 --> 00:43:25.930
about descent with modification
at the level of recipes

00:43:25.930 --> 00:43:29.190
or toolkits or mechanisms
that make bodies,

00:43:29.190 --> 00:43:30.800
is that new organs can come about

00:43:30.800 --> 00:43:33.490
by the modification of ancient recipes.

00:43:33.490 --> 00:43:35.160
Just like we have
descent with modification

00:43:35.160 --> 00:43:36.290
and we can interpret it

00:43:36.290 --> 00:43:38.680
at the level of anatomical structures,

00:43:38.680 --> 00:43:40.420
we can have descent with modification

00:43:40.420 --> 00:43:41.880
at the level of the toolkit,

00:43:41.880 --> 00:43:43.980
the processes, and the genes that compose

00:43:43.980 --> 00:43:47.023
that toolkit that make organs.

00:43:48.910 --> 00:43:51.810
And so, this allows us to
return to Owen's theme, really,

00:43:51.810 --> 00:43:53.790
in the sense that he
was saying, basically,

00:43:53.790 --> 00:43:57.620
that these appendages are the same thing,

00:43:57.620 --> 00:43:58.550
but they're utterly different

00:43:58.550 --> 00:44:00.920
from something like this,
which is the wing of a fly.

00:44:00.920 --> 00:44:02.550
And indeed, when we look at Darwin

00:44:02.550 --> 00:44:04.740
and we follow descent with modification,

00:44:04.740 --> 00:44:07.330
that appears to be correct
in an evolutionary sense,

00:44:07.330 --> 00:44:11.400
is that fly wings have a
separate evolutionary origin

00:44:11.400 --> 00:44:14.543
than do the appendages
of vertebrate animals.

00:44:15.510 --> 00:44:20.020
But when we start to look at
the toolkit and the recipe,

00:44:20.020 --> 00:44:22.350
this convenient distinction

00:44:22.350 --> 00:44:24.443
begins to break down in an odd way.

00:44:25.870 --> 00:44:27.850
So, let's look at a fly leg or wing,

00:44:27.850 --> 00:44:30.240
I have it on the left,
and a limb bud here.

00:44:30.240 --> 00:44:31.760
And what's interesting,
if you can think about,

00:44:31.760 --> 00:44:33.530
and I'm just gonna do an overview of it,

00:44:33.530 --> 00:44:37.200
the biological processes
that determine the pattern

00:44:37.200 --> 00:44:39.480
of these appendages in three dimensions,

00:44:39.480 --> 00:44:43.590
that along this z-axis, the
y-axis, and the x-axis here,

00:44:43.590 --> 00:44:46.580
let's look at the tools that pattern that.

00:44:46.580 --> 00:44:49.710
Well, we already talk about
some of these in the limb.

00:44:49.710 --> 00:44:52.220
And I'm just showing a drawing here,

00:44:52.220 --> 00:44:54.290
which shows if you look at the x-axis,

00:44:54.290 --> 00:44:56.520
it's really the ZPA with Sonic hedgehog,

00:44:56.520 --> 00:44:59.570
and there's another gene which
I didn't talk about, BMP.

00:44:59.570 --> 00:45:01.330
If you look at a fly imaginal disc,

00:45:01.330 --> 00:45:02.900
which looks nothing
like a limb bud at all,

00:45:02.900 --> 00:45:05.400
or the imaginal disc of a wing or a leg,

00:45:05.400 --> 00:45:07.750
they have a hedgehog gene
that's evolutionarily related

00:45:07.750 --> 00:45:09.710
to Sonic hedgehog, and it is turned on

00:45:09.710 --> 00:45:12.552
in the entire sort of posterior half

00:45:12.552 --> 00:45:16.900
of the developing fly imaginal disc.

00:45:16.900 --> 00:45:18.090
And there's another gene, DPP,

00:45:18.090 --> 00:45:21.090
which is turned on just
along the margin here,

00:45:21.090 --> 00:45:24.220
and that, by the way,
is the same gene as BMP,

00:45:24.220 --> 00:45:28.920
if you could trace it in
evolutionary trees of genes.

00:45:28.920 --> 00:45:31.790
What happens when you misexpress
Sonic on the opposite side,

00:45:31.790 --> 00:45:33.720
you remember, we showed
that to you a million times,

00:45:33.720 --> 00:45:38.440
you get a duplicated
fin, or duplicated limb.

00:45:38.440 --> 00:45:40.730
What happens if you misexpress hedgehog,

00:45:40.730 --> 00:45:41.850
its equivalent in the fly,

00:45:41.850 --> 00:45:45.610
wing imaginal disc on the
opposite side, or even this DPP.

00:45:45.610 --> 00:45:46.460
What do you find?

00:45:47.570 --> 00:45:48.920
You find a duplicated wing.

00:45:49.840 --> 00:45:51.640
Okay, these are differently
derived structures,

00:45:51.640 --> 00:45:55.990
but you find duplicate,
same effect, same genes,

00:45:55.990 --> 00:45:58.840
evolutionarily doing similar
kinds of things, equivalent.

00:45:58.840 --> 00:46:00.200
And I can say the same thing

00:46:00.200 --> 00:46:01.800
for genes that are on the y-axis,

00:46:01.800 --> 00:46:02.710
which I'm not gonna get into.

00:46:02.710 --> 00:46:05.980
You have genes like wingless,
which I didn't draw, apterous.

00:46:05.980 --> 00:46:06.813
And here you have genes

00:46:06.813 --> 00:46:09.020
that are wingless as here, too, in LMX1.

00:46:09.020 --> 00:46:12.220
And you also have in the x-axis,
the axis which grows out.

00:46:12.220 --> 00:46:15.290
You have other genes which control the...

00:46:15.290 --> 00:46:17.360
which are within the AER but actually

00:46:17.360 --> 00:46:20.420
are also controlling the
outgrowth of the thing.

00:46:20.420 --> 00:46:23.743
DLX here in distalis, in the
fly leg, but not in the wing.

00:46:24.600 --> 00:46:25.433
So really, if you look at it,

00:46:25.433 --> 00:46:27.190
and just the take-home message is

00:46:27.190 --> 00:46:29.140
here you have two organs,
which by all accounts,

00:46:29.140 --> 00:46:33.060
are different, okay, in
an evolutionary sense.

00:46:33.060 --> 00:46:37.440
Yet the toolkit, the underlying
toolkit that makes them

00:46:37.440 --> 00:46:39.840
is actually looks to be very similar,

00:46:39.840 --> 00:46:43.060
so similar in many ways
that it may be the same

00:46:43.060 --> 00:46:44.300
in an evolutionary sense,

00:46:44.300 --> 00:46:46.300
that it's continuous in doing something.

00:46:47.170 --> 00:46:48.480
This leads me to sort of the final

00:46:48.480 --> 00:46:50.280
sort of sequence of the talk,

00:46:50.280 --> 00:46:52.150
which is to really think
about what this means

00:46:52.150 --> 00:46:54.600
with regard to the origin of organs.

00:46:54.600 --> 00:46:57.990
And there was a analogy, a flawed analogy,

00:46:57.990 --> 00:46:59.830
but an analogy that was very powerful,

00:46:59.830 --> 00:47:03.180
that was set up by Francois Jacob in 1977.

00:47:03.180 --> 00:47:05.510
It's the notion of tinkering.

00:47:05.510 --> 00:47:07.330
He took a very teleological
view of evolution,

00:47:07.330 --> 00:47:08.500
so let's just ignore that for a second.

00:47:08.500 --> 00:47:13.350
But he had an analogy that
has some intuitive power.

00:47:13.350 --> 00:47:15.700
And that is what he says
is evolution doesn't act

00:47:15.700 --> 00:47:18.590
as an engineer who can build
structures from scratch.

00:47:18.590 --> 00:47:21.800
In his mind, evolution
acted as a tinkerer,

00:47:21.800 --> 00:47:23.910
modifying existed odds and ends,

00:47:23.910 --> 00:47:26.300
things that exist to make the new.

00:47:26.300 --> 00:47:28.000
Now, put in non-teleological terms,

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:30.760
what it means is that
the fuel for evolution,

00:47:30.760 --> 00:47:34.700
the variation that natural
selection actually acts on

00:47:34.700 --> 00:47:36.520
is really the result of changes

00:47:36.520 --> 00:47:39.280
to the existing genetic
structure in an organism,

00:47:39.280 --> 00:47:41.150
genetic and developmental
structure in an organism.

00:47:41.150 --> 00:47:42.980
It acts on what exists at every stage.

00:47:42.980 --> 00:47:45.107
And what exists in every
stage are the genes

00:47:45.107 --> 00:47:48.000
and developmental processes,
indeed, much of the toolkit

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:50.263
that's making the organs
of ancestral forms.

00:47:52.140 --> 00:47:53.710
So, this leads me to sort of think about

00:47:53.710 --> 00:47:58.120
when I look at cladograms,
I think of something as,

00:47:58.120 --> 00:48:02.500
how when we deploy this
notion of the Hummer analogy,

00:48:02.500 --> 00:48:05.650
being able to trace the
structure of organs in one way,

00:48:05.650 --> 00:48:07.490
but also the toolkits that pattern them

00:48:07.490 --> 00:48:09.240
and aspects of those toolkits.

00:48:09.240 --> 00:48:11.420
It makes one think of almost
a biological cut and paste,

00:48:11.420 --> 00:48:13.147
and not as much as the Wall Drug Jackalope

00:48:13.147 --> 00:48:15.780
or the Wisconsin Narrows Basscat,

00:48:15.780 --> 00:48:18.160
but it leads to several different notions.

00:48:18.160 --> 00:48:20.440
The first is versions of the same toolkit

00:48:20.440 --> 00:48:22.010
pattern different organs.

00:48:22.010 --> 00:48:23.930
Obviously, we've seen
that with the fly wings

00:48:23.930 --> 00:48:25.800
and the limbs of vertebrates.

00:48:25.800 --> 00:48:29.810
We've seen that in fins and gill arches.

00:48:29.810 --> 00:48:31.670
That ancient tools can be redeployed

00:48:31.670 --> 00:48:32.850
during the origins of new organs.

00:48:32.850 --> 00:48:34.100
That may have been the case

00:48:34.100 --> 00:48:36.580
in the origin of appendages themselves

00:48:36.580 --> 00:48:38.560
from, perhaps, the gill arches

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:42.790
of unfinned ancestors.

00:48:42.790 --> 00:48:44.320
And finally, and this is something

00:48:44.320 --> 00:48:46.570
that my introducer, David Wake,

00:48:46.570 --> 00:48:48.210
has talked about for a long time,

00:48:48.210 --> 00:48:51.410
that is having a common
toolkit, having common processes

00:48:51.410 --> 00:48:54.790
that build bodies makes
the independent evolution

00:48:54.790 --> 00:48:58.423
of similar structures more
likely rather than less likely.

00:49:01.010 --> 00:49:04.240
Nobody's really read Stephen
J. Gould's final tome,

00:49:04.240 --> 00:49:07.760
'cause it's about 1,700
pages, but I actually did.

00:49:07.760 --> 00:49:10.380
I was one of the students
who worked with him.

00:49:10.380 --> 00:49:15.090
He devoted 200 pages, more than
200 pages of his final book

00:49:15.090 --> 00:49:17.800
to looking at the consequences
of conserved genes

00:49:17.800 --> 00:49:20.100
on parallel evolution.

00:49:20.100 --> 00:49:22.130
And I really think he put his finger

00:49:22.130 --> 00:49:24.310
on something that's very important.

00:49:24.310 --> 00:49:27.690
That the independent evolution
of similar structures

00:49:27.690 --> 00:49:29.740
is something that's
gonna be made more common

00:49:29.740 --> 00:49:32.980
rather than less common by
the unity of the toolkit

00:49:32.980 --> 00:49:36.100
that we see in diverse kinds of creatures.

00:49:36.100 --> 00:49:39.580
And this sort of allows us to
return to our opening nose.

00:49:39.580 --> 00:49:42.150
And that basically answering the question

00:49:42.150 --> 00:49:44.040
that we can look at the
nose, and we can say,

00:49:44.040 --> 00:49:46.757
quite confidently, looking at phylogeny,

00:49:47.650 --> 00:49:49.500
evolutionary history, we can say

00:49:49.500 --> 00:49:52.220
that the sort of the
nasal organ of mammals

00:49:52.220 --> 00:49:54.690
is the same thing at the level of organs.

00:49:54.690 --> 00:49:57.540
Scientists are still undecided
about this particular one.

00:49:58.988 --> 00:50:01.370
But yet it's not the
same thing as an organ

00:50:01.370 --> 00:50:02.203
in an evolutionary sense.

00:50:02.203 --> 00:50:04.170
This is the beak of a bird,

00:50:04.170 --> 00:50:06.070
and the proboscis of a paddlefish,

00:50:06.070 --> 00:50:07.750
and the proboscis of a beetle.

00:50:07.750 --> 00:50:10.500
Yet despite that, as these things grow,

00:50:10.500 --> 00:50:13.360
as these things develop, they
use the same general tools

00:50:13.360 --> 00:50:16.223
to form their structures inside.

00:50:17.610 --> 00:50:19.260
So, I wanna close with the same series,

00:50:19.260 --> 00:50:20.643
the same sequence of
things I talked yesterday,

00:50:20.643 --> 00:50:23.322
and that's the power
of thinking with trees.

00:50:23.322 --> 00:50:27.100
We tend, I tend even, when I'm presenting

00:50:27.100 --> 00:50:28.660
to think evolution and present evolution

00:50:28.660 --> 00:50:31.840
as a linear series of
events, a gradual series

00:50:31.840 --> 00:50:34.420
that happens within one species,

00:50:34.420 --> 00:50:36.650
with one set of organs
changes into another species

00:50:36.650 --> 00:50:38.630
with another set of organs, and so forth.

00:50:38.630 --> 00:50:41.060
But we really need to return
to Darwin's original vision,

00:50:41.060 --> 00:50:42.980
of which his actual original
vision is right here,

00:50:42.980 --> 00:50:45.210
which is his notebook with his first tree,

00:50:45.210 --> 00:50:47.190
which is, I think here,

00:50:47.190 --> 00:50:48.840
to the notion of a tree.

00:50:48.840 --> 00:50:50.190
Because the notion of a cut and paste

00:50:50.190 --> 00:50:51.530
becomes quite powerful.

00:50:51.530 --> 00:50:53.570
Because the diversification of creatures

00:50:53.570 --> 00:50:55.820
and their evolutionary development

00:50:55.820 --> 00:50:59.010
of their evolutionary
diversity from one another,

00:50:59.010 --> 00:51:00.980
from their common ancestors.

00:51:00.980 --> 00:51:04.900
As changes happen genetically
within different populations,

00:51:04.900 --> 00:51:07.050
it will be more likely
rather than less likely

00:51:07.050 --> 00:51:09.480
to see similar kinds of
anatomical structures

00:51:09.480 --> 00:51:10.880
arise in different creatures.

00:51:10.880 --> 00:51:14.500
Often times, what we'll
see is whole modules,

00:51:14.500 --> 00:51:18.130
whole assemblages of the
toolkit that makes bodies

00:51:18.130 --> 00:51:20.050
redeployed and turned on in ways

00:51:20.050 --> 00:51:22.060
to make all kinds of new structures.

00:51:22.060 --> 00:51:23.590
And I'd like to close just with a thought

00:51:23.590 --> 00:51:26.370
in integration and in integrative biology,

00:51:26.370 --> 00:51:27.540
and I think in this context,

00:51:27.540 --> 00:51:31.420
we really have a power
to integrative biology.

00:51:31.420 --> 00:51:33.370
Because to understand
the origin of new organs,

00:51:33.370 --> 00:51:36.370
we have new tools, and it's
really how we use those tools

00:51:36.370 --> 00:51:39.890
to answer our questions that
it's so vitally important.

00:51:39.890 --> 00:51:42.370
And we have fossils to
tell us about the sequence

00:51:42.370 --> 00:51:46.400
of anatomical changes that
exist in ancestral states.

00:51:46.400 --> 00:51:50.210
We have embryology to tell
us about how cells interact

00:51:50.210 --> 00:51:51.710
to build organs.

00:51:51.710 --> 00:51:53.570
And now, we have at our disposal,

00:51:53.570 --> 00:51:55.550
understanding of genomes and genomics

00:51:55.550 --> 00:51:57.390
to understand the regulatory elements,

00:51:57.390 --> 00:51:59.430
the elements, the little pieces of DNA,

00:51:59.430 --> 00:52:02.280
and the pieces that bid
to those pieces of DNA

00:52:02.280 --> 00:52:04.540
that actually control developmental events

00:52:04.540 --> 00:52:06.000
in different creatures.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:07.410
Because it's not trivial at all

00:52:07.410 --> 00:52:10.260
if we can link genomics,
fossils, and embryos

00:52:10.260 --> 00:52:12.450
to understand how whole new toolkits

00:52:12.450 --> 00:52:14.590
can be redeployed to make whole new ways

00:52:14.590 --> 00:52:18.540
of living in an ecosystem.

00:52:18.540 --> 00:52:20.210
I'd like to thank, and to close again,

00:52:20.210 --> 00:52:23.580
by thanking my host here at
Berkeley for a marvelous week.

00:52:23.580 --> 00:52:25.100
I'd like to thank you for
being such a great audience.

00:52:25.100 --> 00:52:25.974
Thank you very much.

00:52:25.974 --> 00:52:28.974
(audience applause)

